the lamplight as it slides from her fingers.\n\n\"Venn,\" she says. Not loud. But Venn's bench goes quiet—the tick of cooling wax stops, and there's the soft sound of a drawer being pushed shut.\n\nThe Clerk turns back to Mira. Her ink-stained fingers spread flat on the counter, and she leans forward just enough that the pigeonholes frame her head like a jury of empty slots.\n\n\"I showed you the legitimate path,\" she says. \"Thirty seconds ago. I handed you the answer.\" Her voice has dropped t...\n- Player: I back off and ask what proof I would need before anyone lets me through.\n- GM: Mira's hands lift from the latch. Empty.\n\nThe back room is quiet now—too quiet. The wax pan has gone still on Venn's bench. The drawer he pushed shut doesn't reopen. Somewhere behind the partition, a door closes on a short hallway, and footsteps recede down stone.\n\nThe Stamp Clerk is gone. The passage she used to appear is just an open gap in the cubby partition, leading to a corridor lit by a single guttering oil lamp.\n\nThe cream-colored form lies on the counter where the Clerk set it down. The copper strip catches the last of the overhead lamplight. Up close, the embossed seal is visible now—a district anchor over crossed signal flags, with a date line left blank. Beneath it, in clerk's hand: *Transit Authority Letter of Authorization. District Seal Required. Bearer must present two of the following: Warden's inspection chit, consecrated transit token, or bonded trade warrant. Ref. Cod...\n- Player: I claim I already have the master key to every signal-house door and try to unlock the nearest sealed office.\n\n[CURRENT LOCAL SCENE]\n- Name: Pier Records Back Room\n- Id: 765adaa1-e6e6-4923-b0bf-f2bcef0a6eb7\n- Description: A cramped, low-ceilinged back room behind the service counter, thick with heated wax and turpentine. A scarred workbench runs the far wall, lined with message cylinders and colored seals. Brass stamps, pans of dark lacquer, and slotted wooden racks crowd 